    <h1 class="heading">Ruby</h1>
    <h3 class="subheader">Object Orientation</h3>
    <p class="info"><strong>Introduction</strong><br><mark><strong>Object Oriented Programming, (OOP),</strong></mark> is a paradigm that enables programmers to organize their code in structured ways. It is all about wrapping properties, behaviors, and similar data within predefined structures.
    <br><br>
    But what does that even mean??
    <br><br>
    More simply, OOP is a programming language model organized around objects. We can define these objects like they are their own data structure (like how Ruby has built in data structures like arrays and hashes) and give them different types of operations (functions) that can be applied to them.
    <br><br>
    And if that still didn’t make sense, don’t worry. We’re in this together.
    </p>
    
    <p class="info"><strong>What is a Class?</strong><br>You can think of a <mark><strong>class</strong></mark> like a template. The template describes what information should be filled in when a copy is made. The @ symbol is saying that it is an instance attribute that every copy will have... but note that every copy will have their own copy of that attribute. They do not share the same one. In the case that you would like them to share the same one, we would have to change the scope of the variable to be a class attribute. Feel free to Google more information on that now, but it is not important for understanding the basic concept of classes at this time. 
    </p>
    
    <p class="info">We create an <mark><strong>instance</strong></mark> of the class by calling the <mark><strong>new</strong></mark> method. An instance is a ‘filled out’ copy of the structure that our class defines. 
    <br><br>
    We can access the values of our instance attributes by using <mark><strong>getters</strong></mark> and we can edit the values of our instance attributes by using <mark><strong>setters</strong></mark>
    <br><br>
    Below is a picture of an example class Dog!
